From 0337831dc34cc16047115d92d66c7b53cbd6707e Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Josh Law <objecting@objecting.org>
Date: Sun, 12 Apr 2026 19:41:51 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] lib/base64: fix out-of-bounds read with negative string
 lengths

The base64_decode function accepts a signed int for srclen. If a caller accidentally passes a negative length and padding is false, the function bypasses the srclen == 1 check and proceeds to read up to three bytes from the memory address pointed to by src.

While current kernel callers may not pass negative lengths, library functions accepting signed lengths must guard against underflows to prevent arbitrary out-of-bounds reads.

Fix this by catching any srclen < 2 instead of exactly srclen == 1.

Signed-off-by: Josh Law <objecting@objecting.org>
---
 lib/base64.c | 2 +-
 1 file changed, 1 insertion(+), 1 deletion(-)

diff --git a/lib/base64.c b/lib/base64.c
index 41961a444028..6349afe0ff63 100644
--- a/lib/base64.c
+++ b/lib/base64.c
@@ -164,7 +164,7 @@ int base64_decode(const char *src, int srclen, u8 *dst, bool padding, enum base6
 
 	if (likely(!srclen))
 		return bp - dst;
-	if (padding || srclen == 1)
+	if (padding || srclen < 2)
 		return -1;
 
 	val = (base64_rev_tables[s[0]] << 12) | (base64_rev_tables[s[1]] << 6);
-- 
2.34.1

